# speckit Specification: richards_sudoku (Python + PyQt6)

## Objective
Deliver a cross-platform PyQt6 desktop app (Python 3.13) to create, play, solve, and share multiple Sudoku variants (Standard 9x9, Jigsaw, Str8ts, 1–25). Provide robust persistence, assistance tools, statistics, and deterministic generation/solving within defined performance budgets.

## Scope
- In-scope: UI (PyQt6), puzzle generation/validation/solving, variant management, save/load/import/export (JSON/text), hints, pencil marks, undo/redo, conflict highlighting, timer and stats, difficulty selection, themes and accessibility (light/dark, font sizes, contrast), keyboard and mouse controls, keyboard-only operation.
- Out-of-scope (for now): online services, leaderboards, multiplayer, cloud saves, mobile UI, telemetry.

## Architecture
- Layered modules:
  - generator: seeded generators per variant and difficulty; ensure uniqueness and solvability.
  - solver: backtracking + constraint propagation; reusable validator; deterministic.
  - model: puzzle state, candidates, undo/redo stack, timer, stats, hint limits.
  - persistence: JSON/text import/export; versioned schema; atomic save/load.
  - ui: PyQt6 widgets for grid, controls, dialogs; theme manager; accessibility.
  - services: command bus for undo/redo, hint service, conflict detection.
- Dependency direction: ui -> services -> model -> solver/generator; persistence depends only on model.

## Data and Formats
- Internal board: matrix of cells with value, candidates, region id, fixed/editable flag.
- Variants metadata: region layouts (e.g., Jigsaw masks), constraints, symbols (1-9, 1-25).
- Save schema (JSON): version, variant, difficulty, seed, board state, timer, moves, hints used, undo/redo stack snapshot, theme and font settings.
- Import/export: JSON primary; also support text format with rows of digits plus headers including variant, size, seed, difficulty; validation on import. Prompt user for paths on each save/load/import/export.

## UI/UX
- Grid view: selectable cells with highlight of cell/row/column/region; pencil marks visually distinct; conflict highlight without blocking input.
- Controls: new, load, save, import, export, hint, pencil toggle, undo, redo, difficulty selector, variant selector; keyboard shortcuts for number entry and navigation; keyboard-only support for all actions.
- Themes/accessibility: light/dark presets; adjustable font size (min 6pt); avoid color-only cues; default Arial font; palette and additional fonts to be supplied later.
- Feedback: toast/dialog for save/load/import/export success/failure; hint count visible; timer visible and pauses on save.

## Behavior
- New game: select variant and difficulty; generate with seed; validate solvable and unique; start timer.
- Hint: user-selectable mode per hint invocation (show candidate, auto-fill single cell, multi-cell reveal, or full solution walkthrough); mode can change mid-game; decrement available hints; track count.
- Undo/redo: unbounded stack (practically capped by memory guard); operates on board edits and pencil marks only; timer and hint counters unaffected.
- Conflict detection: continuous checks for row/column/region duplicates; surfaced as highlight.
- Persistence: save/load is atomic; load restores timer, stats, candidates, pencil marks, undo/redo.

## Performance Targets
- Validation: <200ms typical 9x9; solving: <2s typical 9x9 on baseline hardware; scales reasonably for larger grids.
- UI responsiveness: no blocked input during generation/solve; use background workers with progress cues.
- Save/load/import/export: <300ms typical; guard against data loss with temp file then move.
- Memory: bounded candidate tracking and undo/redo; avoid quadratic growth on 1–25 grids.

## Testing
- Unit: solver correctness, generator uniqueness/solvability per difficulty, conflict detection, hint correctness (per hint mode), undo/redo integrity (board edits/pencil marks), stats tracking, persistence round-trip.
- Property/scenario: randomized seeds across variants and sizes; invariants on constraints; import/export fixtures.
- UI smoke: grid render, selection/highlight, pencil marks visibility, hint button availability/modes, undo/redo, theme toggle, keyboard-only flows.
- Performance: benchmarks for solver/generator and persistence budgets; deterministic seeds in tests.
- Tooling: pytest, pytest-qt (qtbot), hypothesis optional.

## Milestones
- MVP (aligns with roadmap): standard 9x9 UI, generation, validate, save/load JSON, timer, pencil marks, undo/redo, basic themes (light/dark, Arial), keyboard-only paths.
- Beta: add Jigsaw, Str8ts, 1–25; hints (multi-mode), conflict highlighting, import/export, difficulty selection, move/hint tracking, end-of-game stats.
- Full: puzzle editor, online sharing, multiplayer timed challenges, cloud saves, mobile-friendly UI, further solver optimization.

## Acceptance Criteria (per PRD/Checklist)
- Users can start, play, and finish standard Sudoku with responsive UI and preserved state on save/load.
- Variants playable with consistent controls and assistance; import/export loads solvable puzzles and remains playable end-to-end.
- Statistics (time, moves, hints) tracked and shown at completion; hint limits enforceable; keyboard-only flows supported.
- Architecture remains modular with typed interfaces and validated inputs; persistence is versioned and backward compatible.
- Meets performance budgets and passes test suite outlined above.
